'''Myōken-ji''' (妙見寺) is a {{ill|Tendai Buddhism|ja|天台宗|12=draft|12=draft}} temple located in {{ill|Takasaki|ja|高崎市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Gunma Prefecture, Japan. Its mountain name (''sangō'') is Sankosan, and its cloister name (''ingō'') is Kisshōin. The temple's principal image is {{ill|Shakyamuni Buddha|ja|釈迦如来|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== History == The founding date of this temple is unclear, but it is traditionally said to have been established in either [[Wadō]] 7 (714) or [[Reiki]] 1 (715) by {{ill|Fujiwara no Tadaaki|ja|藤原忠明|12=draft|12=draft}}, a local official in {{ill|Kōzuke Province|ja|上野国|12=draft|12=draft}}.
According to the "Hanazono Star God Record" (花園星神記), Tadaaki once stayed at the temple. Awakening at midnight, he noticed a bright light rising in the northwest direction. Curious, he sent retainers to investigate and discovered the light emanated from the Kobushi Pond in Reimizu Town. They retrieved a rare turtle with red eyes and a white neck from the water. When Tadaaki presented this turtle to the emperor, it was so highly esteemed that the era name was changed to Reiki ("Holy Turtle").
The temple is mentioned in the {{ill|Shoku Nihongi|ja|続日本紀|12=draft|12=draft}}, compiled in [[Enryaku]] 16 (797), confirming its long-standing history. Previously known as "Shichiseizan Sokusaiji," it has been a site of devotion to {{ill|Myōken Bosatsu|ja|妙見菩薩|12=draft|12=draft}} and was also called "Hitsuji Myōken" (Sheep Myōken). Some scholars link the temple to the {{ill|Tako Kō Monument|ja|多胡碑|12=draft|12=draft}}, particularly its reference to "sheep."
During the {{ill|Jōhei-Tengyō War|ja|承平天慶の乱|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Taira no Yoshifumi|ja|平良文|12=draft|12=draft}}, cornered in the Battle of Someyagawa, followed a mysterious voice to the temple. There, a monk entrusted him with the "Seven-Star Sword," enabling him to gain the protection of Myōken Bosatsu. Myōken deities revered at {{ill|Chichibu Shrine|ja|秩父神社|12=draft|12=draft}} and {{ill|Chiba Shrine|ja|千葉神社|12=draft|12=draft}} were enshrined from this temple.
